Oh come on. Chicago hasn't been *formally* announced, and Microsoft has
been holding a tight reign on Alphas and Beta I (to avert criticism
due to poor performance/unreliability?), but as far as publicity and
marketing are concerned, Microsoft has been putting it about a bit,
to put it mildly. Anyone with Mosaic can look at the Chicago Reviewers
Package/propaganda, which seems to have been distributed and printed
verbatim by every PC magazine under the sun, at least a year before
current ship date estimations. I've seen reviews of the Warp Beta
(including one utter drivel review in the unreadably lowbrow UK
Computer Shopper - the one magazine where I seriously doubt the
reviewers ability to correctly plug in and turn on a computer, and the
only one that doesn't accept e-mail, maybe just as well). They've
all appeared roughly 3 months before ship date, and I've not seen
any IBM Workplace propaganda packages splashed around.

I agree that keeping a new OS aimed at millions of people a secret
is almost impossible. However, how much was known about Ferengi
before it was released? It was not exactly preceded by a 15 month
publicity campaign, the first I heard of it was the official
announcement a few weeks before shipping.

You may be right that IBM and Microsoft are doing the same thing,
but Chicago is currently the grandaddy of all FUD and propaganda
regarding an unreleased product.

Incidentally, I think Borland behave well in this regard. They
could have FUDded much more to slow the bleeding away of dBase
users to FoxPro and Access.

As for the developers, isn't the spec for the so-called
grand unified Win32, there's only one Win32, honest, all
available? What more do you need?

